de.systemagmbh.common.util
Class CSysTimeMeasureStack

java.lang.Object
  de.systemagmbh.common.util.CSysTimeMeasureStack
Deprecated. As of release 2.5, replaced by de.systemagmbh.tools.util.CSysTimeMeasureStack

public class CSysTimeMeasureStack
extends Object

The CSysTimeMeasureStack class can be used to measure how long certain blocks of java code will take to be executed. A timestamp can be pushed on a stack and later the difference between the actual time and the pushed time can be pop'ed again. Also you can peek the time difference. Then you would get it without pop it from the stack.

The following example shows how to use the CSysTimeMeasureStack: 


     public static void main (String arg[])
     {
           CSysTimeMeasureStack.push();
           for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++)
           {
              doSomethingTimeConsuming();
           }
           System.out.printlnt ("Time for first loop: " + CSysTimeMeasureStack.peek());
           CSysTimeMeasureStack.push();
           for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++)
           {
              doAnotherTimeConsumingThing();
           }
           System.out.printlnt ("Time for second loop: " + CSysTimeMeasureStack.pop());
           System.out.printlnt ("Total time: " + CSysTimeMeasureStack.pop());
     }

Calculates the time difference between the actual time and the last timestamp which was pushed on the stack. This time is delivered in seconds (with milliseconds as fraction). The last timestamp of the stack will be removed from the stack by this operation.
